function generateWhyText() {
    return "Why is letter writing important? Writing letters to elected officials is a great way to let your opinion be known to your representative. Their job is to represent not just their own opinion, but the population that they serve. The ACLU makes a great point in their guide to letter writing, saying, “Many legislators believe that a letter represents not only the position of the writer but also many other constituents who did not take the time to write.”";
}

function generateWhoText() {
    return "Speaking of writing letters to representatives, who can you write a letter to? You can write a letter to any elected official, but that doesn’t mean you should. You should more often than not write letters to elected officials that specifically represent you  (your city, district, etc.) The officials who do not represent your area are less likely to care about your opinion, simply because it’s not their responsibility to reflect you. This is not always the case though. For example, if a California Assembly Member is the chair of a committee voting on a topic you care about, and your assemblyperson is not on the committee, you can write to the chair, as they are the lead within the committee.";
}

function generateWhereText() {
    return "Sending your letter: Now that your letter is written, it’s time to send it! You can either email your letter or mail it to the official’s office. I prefer physical mailing because it feels more personal and intentional, but that’s just my preference. Public email and office addresses can be found on the official’s website. Before even starting your letter though, I recommend you check to make sure their addresses are displayed.";
}

